@Liechti As for Japanese, the rule is extremely similar. In Korean it is somewhat less common to see dates written with Chinese characters (sometimes hangul, though).

Japan has one extra issue I haven't checked whether is handled here: imperial dates. These are very easy to detect when they have the era name (appearing, for example, as 平成, 平, "Heisei", or "H." followed by date characters) but require a conversion table to translate to an ISO year. Sometimes they are not labeled, so one has to assume that a year value less than, say, 100 is actually a current-era imperial year (sometimes which era was "current" at the time of a document's creation is only discernable with some extra context, though).

Numbers can be tricky because years may be in traditional characters, half-width western characters, or full-width western characters (this is a perennial issue in interpreting Japanese numbers, though, only ever solved very well by game libraries, tbh -- that is to say, Japanese users will not be surprised in the slightest for full functionality to be lacking, but will be pleasantly surprised if it exists).

@tepickering The maximum in the aperture mask won't always be 1.0 because the aperture can be smaller than a pixel (e.g. in your `rectangular_overlap_grid` example, the size is 0.3 x 2 pixels).  If you change your `circular_overlap_grid` example to use the exact method, then it's max shouldn't be 1.0 either (it should be `np.pi * 0.45**2 = 0.6361725`).

However, I don't think the maximum should ever be *more* than 1.0.  @astrofrog?
