@cel4, I see, so you want all Python packages you already have in your root environment to be available when using Python kernels.

Well, you can install them too in your `test-r` environment without wasting disk space. conda only makes (hard) symlinks between the place where your packages are located and a directory inside `test-r` (`site-packages` for Python packages). That's how package installation works in conda for all packages :-)

The thing is conda environments are precisely designed to let you try different versions of the same library, or a combination of different versions of different libraries. That's why I (also) closed the issue initially ;-)

